## 4. Predictive Utility as a Sufficient Statistic (The "Dark Matter" Corollary)

The Flatness Lemma shows that the model can encode $G$. The following condition explains why it permanently allocates non-zero parameter volume to $G$ despite its low empirical frequency.

**Corollary 4.1 (Predictive Utility Threshold).**
Let $G$ be the generative grammar of the rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$. Define the restricted optimum:
$$\theta_{-G} := \arg\min_{\theta' : \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta' = 0} \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta')$$
where $\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}$ is the loss on the full web distribution $P_{\text{web}}$. If there exists a marginal improvement $\delta > 0$ such that:
$$\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta) \leq \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta_{-G}) - \delta$$
then the $G$-subspace receives a persistent gradient signal from the aggregate gravitational pull of the broader distribution.

*Intuition:* The model does not care about $x_{\text{rare}}$ per se. It cares that knowing $G$ makes it slightly better at predicting trillions of common tokens (e.g., using state-transition logic to improve next-word prediction in technical recipes or code). This tiny, ubiquitous gradient prevents the $G$-subspace from collapsing under weight decay or SGD noise, acting as a persistent restoring force in the continuous-time SDE limit.

