# Appendix A: Complete Proof of Theorem 5.1

**Theorem 5.1.** *Under (A1) and (A2), the optimization trajectory converges to $\mathcal{M}_G$, the representation has intrinsic dimension $d \ll D$, and the model exhibits compositional generalization for any $x' \sim G$.*

**Proof.**
*Part 1 (Convergence):* Consider the gradient flow $\dot{\theta}_t = -\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) + \xi_t$ with $\text{Cov}(\xi_t) \approx \frac{\eta}{B}H(\theta_t)$. Under (A2), the space decomposes orthogonally into $\mathcal{M}_G \oplus \mathcal{M}_{\text{common}} \oplus \mathcal{N}$. Let $\mathcal{C}_m, \mathcal{C}_g$ be memorization and compression solutions with $\mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_m) \approx \mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_g) \approx 0$. The effective loss $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}} = \mathcal{L} + \frac{\eta}{2B}\text{Tr}(H)$ is strictly lower at $\mathcal{C}_g$ due to distributed curvature vs. sharp token-embedding peaks. By LaSalle's Invariance Principle, $\theta_t \to \mathcal{M}_G$.
*Part 2 (Dimensionality):* $d = \text{rank}(\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} F \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G})$. Under (A1), $G$ minimizes description length, parameterizable by $d = O(\text{Kolmogorov}(G))$ primitives. FIM eigenvalues satisfy $\lambda_k > \epsilon$ for $k \leq d$ and $\lambda_k \approx 0$ otherwise. Thus $d \ll D$.
*Part 3 (Generalization):* For $x' \sim G$, $f_{\theta^*}(x')$ depends only on projections onto $\mathcal{T}_{\theta^*}\mathcal{M}_G$. By restricted universal approximation, the model implements $\Phi_G: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{T}_{\theta^*}\mathcal{M}_G$ evaluating the axioms in $\mathcal{M}_G$, yielding the unique logical continuation. $\square$

