# Appendix C: Spectral Analysis & Block-Diagonal Dominance

**Proposition C.1.** *For $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, disjoint concepts satisfy $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j}\|_F \leq \mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P)}/\sqrt{D})$ w.h.p.*

**Proof Sketch.** $F = \frac{1}{N}\sum g_n g_n^\top$. For disjoint concepts, $g_n^{(i)} \perp g_m^{(j)}$ semantically. In $\mathbb{R}^D$, random vectors concentrate; inner products scale as $\mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{D})$. By matrix concentration (Tropp, 2015), cross-block norms vanish as $D \to \infty$, establishing asymptotic block-diagonality. $\square$

---

# Appendix D: Lyapunov Stability Analysis

Let $V(t) = \|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta(t)\|^2$. Under weight decay $\lambda$ and utility $\delta$:
$$\frac{dV}{dt} = -2 \langle \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta, \nabla \mathcal{L} + \lambda \theta - \xi \rangle \geq 2\delta - 2\lambda V(t) + \text{noise}$$
Ignoring martingale terms: $\frac{d\mathbb{E}[V]}{dt} \geq 2\delta - 2\lambda \mathbb{E}[V] \implies \mathbb{E}[V(t)] \geq \frac{\delta}{\lambda}(1-e^{-2\lambda t}) + V(0)e^{-2\lambda t}$. As $t \to \infty$, $\mathbb{E}[V] \geq \delta/\lambda$. The condition $\delta > \lambda \|\theta^*\|^2$ acts as a signal-to-decay ratio, guaranteeing persistent subspace allocation. $\square$

